1
00:00:01,887 --> 00:00:09,753
Namo dasa bhagavato arahato samasambuddhasa

2
00:00:10,577 --> 00:00:34,020
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:39,097 --> 00:00:39,698
Very good.

4
00:00:40,979 --> 00:00:48,210
So last week we tackled this very cryptic, couldn't have, saying from the Buddha, this very cryptic teaching.

5
00:00:48,229 --> 00:00:52,176
He couldn't have reduced his teaching any further, I don't think.

6
00:00:53,177 --> 00:00:55,341
It was about all Bahir of the Barcloth.

7
00:00:55,841 --> 00:01:04,293
So I said that this week we would actually read the discourse and revise what we said, because it's quite difficult, really.

8
00:01:04,730 --> 00:01:14,102
So the collection that this belongs to, by the way, is called the Udana, U-D-A-N-A.

9
00:01:14,462 --> 00:01:20,131
I'll try to remember to put it in the chat box for you, which you can buy as a little booklet.

10
00:01:20,230 --> 00:01:22,033
It's translated by John Ireland.

11
00:01:22,593 --> 00:01:24,516
So that's where this translation comes from.

12
00:01:25,617 --> 00:01:27,320
Okay, the Bahia Sutta.

13
00:01:27,620 --> 00:01:29,082
This is about Bahia.

14
00:01:29,569 --> 00:01:42,626
Thus have I heard, at one time the Lord was staying near Sabati in the Jeta Wood at Anathipindika's monastery, and at that time Bahira the Barcloth was living by the seashore at Suparaka.

15
00:01:43,328 --> 00:01:48,355
He was respected, revered, honoured, venerated and given homage.

16
00:01:48,334 --> 00:01:54,260
and was one who obtained the requisites of robes, alms, food, lodging, and medicines."

17
00:01:54,281 --> 00:02:06,594
Now, we said last week that he was probably a follower of a particular Brahmin sect, depending on the Upanishads, and that their signature was wearing bark cloth.

18
00:02:06,614 --> 00:02:14,122
But here, it's really talking about the myth that arose from him.

19
00:02:14,103 --> 00:02:21,772
whereby he gets shipwrecked and he must have had a Damascene moment out at sea because when he lands, he doesn't want to be a merchant anymore.

20
00:02:22,413 --> 00:02:28,981
He wants to be a Samana, an ascetic, and he gains the respect of everybody.

21
00:02:29,622 --> 00:02:37,612
And these four requisites, robes, arms, food, lodging and medicines, that's the requisites of the Buddhist order.

22
00:02:37,592 --> 00:02:39,094
It's really basic, isn't it?

23
00:02:39,235 --> 00:02:40,798
That's all you need to live.

24
00:02:41,117 --> 00:02:47,987
There's something to wear, something to eat, a roof over your head, and medicine when you're sick.

25
00:02:50,350 --> 00:02:55,258
So now, while he was in seclusion, this reflection arose in the mind of Bahir of the Barcloth.

26
00:02:56,038 --> 00:03:01,727
Am I one of those in the world who are Arahats and who have entered the path of Arahatship?

27
00:03:02,180 --> 00:03:05,086
And the word Arahat is an honorific, really.

28
00:03:05,106 --> 00:03:10,439
It's the blessed one or the holy one or something like that.

29
00:03:11,162 --> 00:03:14,349
But of course, it's given to somebody who's completed the path.

30
00:03:15,258 --> 00:03:22,425
Then a Devata, who was a former blood relation of Bahir of the Barcloth, understood this reflection in his mind.

31
00:03:23,066 --> 00:03:32,977
Being compassionate and wishing to benefit him, she approached Bahir and said, You, Bahir, are neither an Arahat, nor have you entered the path to Arahatship.

32
00:03:33,657 --> 00:03:40,405
You do not follow that practice whereby you could be an Arahat or enter the path of Arahatship.

33
00:03:41,145 --> 00:03:42,507
That's a bit crushing, isn't it?

34
00:03:42,526 --> 00:03:44,909
I mean, a poor man's living.

35
00:03:44,889 --> 00:03:48,896
doing the best he can, and this Devatas told him he's wasting his time.

36
00:03:50,118 --> 00:03:58,594
Then he asks, in the world, including the Devas, all the gods, who are the Arahats, and who have entered the path of Arahatship?

37
00:03:59,977 --> 00:04:04,626
This there is Bahia, in a far country, a town called Savati.

38
00:04:04,846 --> 00:04:08,652
There the Lord now lives, who is an Arahat and fully enlightened one.

39
00:04:08,954 --> 00:04:15,806
That Lord Bahir is indeed an Arahant, and he teaches the Dharma for the realization of Arahantship.

40
00:04:16,726 --> 00:04:27,285
Then Bahir of the Batcloth, profoundly stirred by the words of that Devata, then and there departed from Suparaka, stopping only one night everywhere along the way.

41
00:04:27,685 --> 00:04:34,557
He went to Sarvati, where the Lord was staying at the Jeta Wood at Anathipindika's monastery.

42
00:04:35,413 --> 00:04:40,903
Now, at that time, a number of bhikkhus were walking up and down, doing walking meditation in the open air.

43
00:04:41,302 --> 00:04:49,295
Then Bahir the Barcloth approached those bhikkhus and said, Where, revered sirs, is the Lord now living, the Arahat, the fully enlightened one?

44
00:04:50,237 --> 00:04:53,622
We wish to see the Lord who is an Arahat, the fully enlightened one.

45
00:04:54,463 --> 00:04:58,350
The Lord, Bahir, has gone on arms round among the houses.

46
00:04:58,987 --> 00:05:02,550
Then Bahiya hurriedly left the Jeta Grove, entering Sabati.

47
00:05:02,571 --> 00:05:06,254
He saw the Lord walking for alms food in Sabati.

48
00:05:07,276 --> 00:05:21,670
Pleasing, lovely to see, with calm senses and tranquil mind, attained to perfect poise and calm, controlled, a perfected one, watchful with restrained senses.

49
00:05:22,451 --> 00:05:25,653
So that's a classic trope describing the Buddha.

50
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:39,119
On seeing the Lord, he approached, fell down with his head at the Lord's feet and said, teach me Dharma, Lord, teach me Dharma, Sugata, so that it will be for my good and the happiness for a long time.

51
00:05:39,901 --> 00:05:44,588
This Sugata translates literally as well gone.

52
00:05:46,250 --> 00:05:50,697
It obviously means somebody who's transcended, gone to Nirvana.

53
00:05:52,583 --> 00:05:58,512
Upon being spoken to thus, the Lord said to Bahir the Barcloth, it is an unsuitable time, Bahir.

54
00:05:58,531 --> 00:06:00,735
We've entered among the houses for alms food.

55
00:06:01,637 --> 00:06:10,552
A second time, Bahir said to the Lord, it is difficult to know for certain, revered sir, how long the Lord will live and how long I will live.

56
00:06:10,891 --> 00:06:18,944
Teach me, Dharma Lord, teach me, Dharma Sugata, so that it will be for my good and happiness for a long time.

57
00:06:18,925 --> 00:06:23,791
A second time the Lord said to Bahir, it is an unsuitable time, Bahir.

58
00:06:23,831 --> 00:06:26,375
We have entered among the houses for alms food.

59
00:06:27,697 --> 00:06:29,240
But Bahir wouldn't give up, Buzi.

60
00:06:29,680 --> 00:06:37,350
A third time Bahir said to the Lord, it is difficult to know for certain, revered sir, how long the Lord will live and how long I will live.

61
00:06:37,411 --> 00:06:38,793
Teach me Dharma, Lord.

62
00:06:38,853 --> 00:06:45,523
Teach me Dharma, Sugata, so that it will be for my good and happiness for a long time.

63
00:06:45,502 --> 00:06:49,209
Now, this is one of these things that perhaps was part of the age.

64
00:06:49,790 --> 00:06:56,281
You could ask three times, and if the answer was still no, there was no point in asking again.

65
00:06:56,802 --> 00:07:02,533
So this time, the Buddha took pity on Porobahiya, and he said this,

66
00:07:02,512 --> 00:07:05,538
Here in bahía you should train yourself thus.

67
00:07:06,139 --> 00:07:08,802
In the seen will be merely what is seen.

68
00:07:09,384 --> 00:07:12,048
In the heard will be merely what is heard.

69
00:07:12,668 --> 00:07:15,273
In the sensed will be merely what is sensed.

70
00:07:16,035 --> 00:07:19,319
In the cognized will be merely what is cognized.

71
00:07:19,480 --> 00:07:22,384
In this way you should train yourself bahía.

72
00:07:22,764 --> 00:07:26,951
Okay, so now this is referring directly to our vipassana practice.

73
00:07:27,809 --> 00:07:34,262
So the Buddha categorizes consciousnesses according to the sense base.

74
00:07:35,403 --> 00:07:44,281
So you have eye consciousness, ear consciousness, nose, taste, and body consciousness, and sense.

75
00:07:44,565 --> 00:07:45,927
the mind consciousness.

76
00:07:46,047 --> 00:07:52,194
So what the mind is aware of, of course, is the internal life, the interior life of emotions and thoughts.

77
00:07:52,874 --> 00:07:59,281
So these are your six bases, and it's upon these bases that consciousness arises.

78
00:07:59,680 --> 00:08:03,285
Okay.

79
00:08:03,944 --> 00:08:10,471
So he says, so when, Bahir, when you are in the scene, when for you in the scene,

80
00:08:10,874 --> 00:08:27,259
is merely what is seen, in the heard is merely what is heard, in the sensed, which means smelling and tasting, in the sensed will be merely what is sensed, in the cognized is merely what is cognized, then by here you will not be with that.

81
00:08:28,540 --> 00:08:32,427
When by here you are not with that, you will not be in that.

82
00:08:33,182 --> 00:08:40,350
When by here you are not in that, then by here you will be neither here nor beyond, nor in between the two.

83
00:08:40,750 --> 00:08:42,192
Just this is the end of suffering.

84
00:08:42,732 --> 00:08:47,158
Now, he's pointing, he's saying to Bahiyya, you will not be in that.

85
00:08:47,337 --> 00:08:58,110
Now, remember, if we go back to this Upanishad, it's talking about the...

86
00:08:58,477 --> 00:09:08,907
The unknown knower, right, is always pointing to somebody, the one who understands, the censor, etc., etc.

87
00:09:09,628 --> 00:09:14,912
So now what Bahiyya seems to have been doing is looking for this knower.

88
00:09:15,773 --> 00:09:17,214
And of course, he's not finding it.

89
00:09:17,815 --> 00:09:28,384
So the Buddha tries to avert him from that and draw him down to the level where he's just experiencing things without the sense of I.

90
00:09:29,173 --> 00:09:34,921
So at that very base level, there's always a sense base.

91
00:09:36,263 --> 00:09:41,609
And a sense base has some object that it's sensing.

92
00:09:42,649 --> 00:09:47,275
So obviously, if you've got eyes and you're looking, then you'll see something.

93
00:09:47,375 --> 00:09:48,697
Like for instance, now you're seeing me.

94
00:09:49,458 --> 00:09:58,809
Now, those two then have to have some way of relating that information

95
00:09:59,278 --> 00:10:02,442
onto something that can be seen, can be known.

96
00:10:03,003 --> 00:10:04,784
And that's what consciousness is.

97
00:10:04,825 --> 00:10:08,950
That's the candor consciousness, the consciousness of the aggregates.

98
00:10:08,970 --> 00:10:12,533
All these consciousness are dependent on a sense base.

99
00:10:12,995 --> 00:10:13,274
Okay?

100
00:10:14,216 --> 00:10:21,544
Now, in our meditation, you see, what we're trying to do is to get down to that level where there isn't an I.

101
00:10:22,164 --> 00:10:25,489
What happens normally is we see something,

102
00:10:26,532 --> 00:10:28,054
We don't see it as it is.

103
00:10:28,395 --> 00:10:33,345
We see it within a category, which is our conceptual understanding.

104
00:10:34,307 --> 00:10:40,479
So when I see, for instance, an apple, I don't see that apple as something distinct and spare.

105
00:10:40,918 --> 00:10:44,405
I see it within my concepts of what apples are.

106
00:10:44,385 --> 00:10:50,693
And depending on that concept, I'll be able to say to myself, well, this is a sweet apple or it's not so sweet.

107
00:10:51,153 --> 00:10:53,716
And then, of course, there's I like sweet apples.

108
00:10:53,998 --> 00:10:55,458
I don't like unsweet apples.

109
00:10:56,139 --> 00:10:58,682
And then once you've said that, you have a relationship with it.

110
00:10:59,203 --> 00:11:04,210
I want a sweet apple or simply want a sweet apple.

111
00:11:04,389 --> 00:11:08,195
And then you get the I want a sweet apple.

112
00:11:09,135 --> 00:11:14,022
Now, what he's asking Bahia to do is to cut through that whole thing.

113
00:11:14,474 --> 00:11:21,922
mentation dependent on a delusion of an eye and get down to basics.

114
00:11:21,942 --> 00:11:31,731
And once he does that, of course, he recognizes that there is something which is aware of what's on that screen of consciousness.

115
00:11:32,833 --> 00:11:41,663
And that separation allows him to make the insight of what he really is before he becomes an eye.

116
00:11:43,059 --> 00:11:47,966
Now, I hope that hasn't confused you completely, right?

117
00:11:48,788 --> 00:11:50,130
The teaching is quite difficult.

118
00:11:50,730 --> 00:12:00,326
So when he says you are not with that, in other words, you don't identify with the object, right?

119
00:12:00,346 --> 00:12:04,010
By way of conceptual understanding, the apple, right?

120
00:12:04,371 --> 00:12:05,693
You're not in that.

121
00:12:05,734 --> 00:12:09,580
You're not identifying with the sense base, right?

122
00:12:09,919 --> 00:12:11,903
The taste, the sense of taste.

123
00:12:12,607 --> 00:12:24,683
And when you don't identify with that, what comes up on the screen is pure without the manipulation, the distortion of liking, not liking, wanting, not wanting.

124
00:12:25,284 --> 00:12:26,446
Okay.

125
00:12:26,606 --> 00:12:34,056
And that's when we're able to see that there is something which is distinct from everything that we're experiencing.

126
00:12:34,857 --> 00:12:37,221
And that's the process of awakening.

127
00:12:37,701 --> 00:12:38,261
That's what it is.

128
00:12:39,423 --> 00:12:54,360
Okay, so then he says, now through this brief Dharma teaching of the Lord, the mind of Bahir the Barcloth was immediately freed from the taints without grasping.

129
00:12:54,559 --> 00:12:58,806
Then the Lord, having instructed by here with this brief instruction, went away.

130
00:12:59,166 --> 00:13:00,948
So now this is the point.

131
00:13:00,989 --> 00:13:04,173
This is what happens when we become fully liberated.

132
00:13:04,514 --> 00:13:06,736
We are freed from the taints.

133
00:13:06,756 --> 00:13:08,740
Now the word is asawa.

134
00:13:09,321 --> 00:13:15,469
And there is in that word the meaning, a word su, which means to flow.

135
00:13:16,230 --> 00:13:18,913
So it's like the corruptions are flowing out of us.

136
00:13:19,294 --> 00:13:22,980
Sometimes they're called inflows, sometimes outflows.

137
00:13:22,960 --> 00:13:31,291
And they are the basic delusions that are affecting our lives for the worse, of course.

138
00:13:32,052 --> 00:13:37,240
So the first one is the taint craving for sensual pleasure, right?

139
00:13:38,061 --> 00:13:39,722
Craving for sensual pleasure.

140
00:13:40,364 --> 00:13:44,109
The second one is the craving for existence.

141
00:13:44,129 --> 00:13:46,692
In other words, always becoming, right?

142
00:13:46,732 --> 00:13:51,499
That's why, you know, anytime death approaches us, we panic, right?

143
00:13:52,205 --> 00:13:55,731
So we want to continue from moment after moment.

144
00:13:56,052 --> 00:13:57,335
And we want to be somebody.

145
00:13:57,615 --> 00:13:59,740
We're always redefining ourselves.

146
00:14:00,942 --> 00:14:08,355
And finally, of course, the taint of ignorance, which, of course, is not understanding the way things really are.

147
00:14:09,057 --> 00:14:11,282
So he's freed of all that.

148
00:14:11,763 --> 00:14:14,989
And because he's freed of all that, he's come to the end of suffering.

149
00:14:16,774 --> 00:14:24,152
So then, of course, not long after the Lord's departure, a cow with a young calf attacked Bahia of the Barcloth and killed him.

150
00:14:25,279 --> 00:14:37,712
When the Lord, having walked for alms food in Sarvati, was returning from alms room with a number of bhikkhus, on departing from the town, he saw that bhikkhu of that Bahir of the Barcloth had died.

151
00:14:38,734 --> 00:14:48,524
Seeing this, he said to the bhikkhus, Bhikkhus, take Bahir's body, put it on a litter, carry it away and burn it and make a stupa for it.

152
00:14:48,923 --> 00:14:51,826
Your companion in the holy life has died.

153
00:14:52,481 --> 00:14:55,226
So a stupa would be a mound in those days, that's all.

154
00:14:56,168 --> 00:14:59,475
Very well, revered sir, the bhikkhus replied to the Lord.

155
00:14:59,937 --> 00:15:06,129
Taking Bahiya's body, they put it on a litter, carried it away and burnt it, and made a stupa for it.

156
00:15:07,711 --> 00:15:12,380
Then they went to the Lord, prostrated themselves, and sat down to one side.

157
00:15:13,677 --> 00:15:20,565
Sitting there, those bhikkhus said to the Lord, Bahir's body has been burnt, revered sir, and a stupa has been made for it.

158
00:15:21,304 --> 00:15:22,826
What is his destiny?

159
00:15:23,027 --> 00:15:25,850
What is his future birth?

160
00:15:25,870 --> 00:15:29,394
Bhikkhus, Bahir of the Barcloth was a wise man.

161
00:15:29,453 --> 00:15:36,461
He practiced according to the Dharma and did not trouble me by disputing about Dharma.

162
00:15:37,222 --> 00:15:42,148
Bhikkhus, Bahir of the Barcloth has attained final nibbana.

163
00:15:43,663 --> 00:15:48,052
Now, I love the way this little phrase has been put in there.

164
00:15:48,754 --> 00:15:52,942
So did not trouble me by disputing about Dharma.

165
00:15:52,964 --> 00:15:59,277
So he was constantly hassled by people, you know, questioning what he understood, what he taught.

166
00:15:59,878 --> 00:16:03,225
I find that a lovely little phrase to tell you something about the Buddha's life.

167
00:16:05,331 --> 00:16:10,817
Then on realizing this significance, the Lord uttered on that occasion this inspired utterance.

168
00:16:10,979 --> 00:16:17,066
Okay, so this is where he's stating what nirvana is, okay?

169
00:16:17,086 --> 00:16:26,155
Where neither water, nor yet earth, nor fire, nor air, find a foothold, gain a foothold.

170
00:16:27,256 --> 00:16:34,865
There gleam no stars, no sun sheds light, there shines no moon.

171
00:16:35,403 --> 00:16:40,087
Yet, there no darkness reigns.

172
00:16:40,528 --> 00:16:41,708
Okay?

173
00:16:41,729 --> 00:16:48,676
So the first, of course, is our physicality, which, of course, includes the whole psychophysical organism.

174
00:16:49,296 --> 00:16:54,942
We're neither water, these are the four great elements, water, earth, fire, and air.

175
00:16:57,264 --> 00:17:01,207
And then the outer world, the material world that we live in.

176
00:17:01,389 --> 00:17:09,085
Gleam no stars, no sun sheds lights, there shines no moon, yet no darkness reigns.

177
00:17:10,326 --> 00:17:18,762
Now, I was listening to a talk by Bhikkhu Bodhi, in which he was asked, what is the understanding of this Nirvana, you see?

178
00:17:19,443 --> 00:17:22,871
And he said that in the Theravada Buddhism, there were two understandings.

179
00:17:23,612 --> 00:17:25,255
The first one was that

180
00:17:25,807 --> 00:17:37,123
When you finally purified your heart and it's time to become liberated, the five khandhas, the psychophysical organism, comes to an end, and that's it.

181
00:17:37,983 --> 00:17:48,458
Now, I know people who believe that, that that's what the Buddha's teaching, and I cannot, I just cannot know the difference between that and annihilation.

182
00:17:49,130 --> 00:17:54,095
And the Buddha often in the discourses says he is not teaching annihilation.

183
00:17:54,355 --> 00:18:00,320
He says the only things that are annihilated are greed, hatred, and delusion.

184
00:18:01,821 --> 00:18:14,714
And then Bhikkhu Bodhi says the second reason, the second understanding, which is the traditional understanding, is that when the psychophysical organism, the five khandhas, come to an end,

185
00:18:15,336 --> 00:18:20,304
There is a transcendent experience.

186
00:18:20,324 --> 00:18:24,711
And that's what this, yet there no darkness reigns, is pointing to.

187
00:18:24,730 --> 00:18:34,404
And if you actually get that book, the Udana, the inspired verses of the Buddha, you'll see that there's a whole section on Nirvana.

188
00:18:34,424 --> 00:18:37,490
And they're all basically pointing to the same thing.

189
00:18:40,894 --> 00:18:44,500
Dogen Zenji, actually, the great Zen master,

190
00:18:45,019 --> 00:18:51,112
talked about his moment of liberation by saying, the body and mind fell away.

191
00:18:51,152 --> 00:18:54,178
The body and mind fell away.

192
00:18:56,343 --> 00:18:57,965
That's another way of stating it.

193
00:18:58,688 --> 00:19:16,086
So then he goes on, when a sage, a Brahmin, has come to know this for himself through his own wise experience, insight experience, then he is freed from form and formless, freed from pleasure and from pain.

194
00:19:16,106 --> 00:19:17,808
In other words, he's gone beyond.

195
00:19:17,949 --> 00:19:26,838
He's gone beyond all the amazing stuff you can get from absorption techniques, and he's gone beyond all that we can imagine.

196
00:19:26,818 --> 00:19:55,797
experience pleasure or pain from our physicality so he's always pointing to something which is beyond now he doesn't want to call it he doesn't want to give it a name he doesn't want to substantiate it because then you end up like by here completely confused looking for your soul by looking for your eternal self and that's why he's constantly pointing to it but not giving it a name of course in later buddhism

197
00:19:56,198 --> 00:20:06,151
In Mahayana Buddhism, they began talking about it as the Dharmakaya, the body of the truth, sometimes Buddha nature.

198
00:20:07,873 --> 00:20:12,419
This inspired utterance was spoken by the Lord also.

199
00:20:13,319 --> 00:20:15,122
So did I hear.

200
00:20:18,205 --> 00:20:18,767
Very good.

201
00:20:18,787 --> 00:20:25,715
Well, as usual, I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused confusion.

202
